<statement>
<p>A triangle has sides with lengths <m>\displaystyle{a}={7.00}</m>, <m>\displaystyle{b}={9.43}</m>, and <m>\displaystyle{c}={10.72}</m>. Calculate all of the angles of this triangle.</p>
<p>A=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{a}={7.00}</m>)</p>
<p>
  B=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{b}={9.43}</m>)</p>
<p>
  C=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{c}={10.72}</m>)</p>
<p>Round to two decimal places.</p>


</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li>40.02</li><li>60.02</li><li>81.18</li></ul></p><p>Because we have all three sides, we can use the law of cosines for the first angle.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{7}^{{2}}={9.43}^{{2}}+{10.72}^{{2}}-{2}{\left({9.43}\right)}{\left({10.72}\right)}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{49}={88.9249}+{114.9184}-{202.1792}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{154.8433}=-{202.1792}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{0.76587156344471}={\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{A}={40.015407404737}={40.02}</m>.</p>
<p>For a second angle, we can use the shorter law of sines.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{\sin{{\left({40.015407404737}\right)}}}}{{7.00}}=\frac{{\sin{{\left({B}\right)}}}}{{9.43}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{0.98981233005509}={\sin{{\left({B}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{B}={\arcsin{{\left({0.98981233005509}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{B}={60.020496386213}\approx{60.02}</m></p>
<p>The third angle we can calculate using the angle sum property.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{40.015407404737}+{60.020496386213}+{C}={180}^{\circ}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{C}={81.182080039984}\approx{81.18}</m></p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>

